Date: Wed 20 Mar 2013
From: Alberto Acosta <amacosta@travelersmedical.com> [edited]


I was pleased to read your report identifying a long standing and often overlooked potential public health concern.

_Trypanosoma cruzi_, the etiologic agent of Chagas disease, is found only in the western hemisphere, and its natural vector, the hemiptera insects, belonging to Family Reduviidae, subfamily Triatominae, have an extensive geographic distribution roughly from the middle of Argentina and Chile up through the middle of the United States (1). These aggressive, nocturnal insects are popularly known as "kissing bugs" or "assassin bugs" in the southern United States, as "pitos" or "vinchucas" in Spanish America, and as "barbeiros" in Portuguese Brazil.

The most important factor predisposing humans to infection is the transfer of _T. cruzi_ infected Reduviidae from the sylvatic cycle of the vector to the domestic cycle: namely, the deposition of the vector into human dwellings. Continuity between cycles is known to occur (2, 3).

The Reduviidae insects conceal themselves in the walls and roofs of dwellings and come out at night to feed on the human inhabitants. In areas highly endemic for Chagas disease, badly infected houses have been estimated to contain up to several thousand insects, 70 percent of which may be infected (4). In such situations, the prevalence of infection of the human inhabitants is close to 100 percent (4). Significantly, in areas where the insect adaptation to houses has not occurred, only a few isolated cases of Chagas disease are found even though the infection rate of sylvatic Reduviidae may be high (5).

In the United States, early seroprevalence studies estimated that 2-4 percent of the human population in certain rural areas of the southwest may be _T. cruzi_-infected (6). The ProMED moderator's note cited reports of several autochthonous cases of human _T. cruzi_ infection in Arizona and Louisiana.

Autochthonous cases of _T. cruzi_ infection have been reported from other areas of the United States, including California and Tennessee (7-10). It is interesting to note that _T. cruzi_ has been isolated from sylvatic animals as far north as the state of Maryland (11), but no human infection has been reported there.

With the reported apparent increase in the number of Reduviidae insects in the southwestern United States and the continued encroachment on rural areas by urban development, there is an increasing potential for the transfer of Reduviidae from the sylvatic to the domestic cycle. This may in turn contribute to a potential increase in cases of autochthonous _T. cruzi_ infection in the United States.

1. Zeledon, R. Epidemiology, modes of transmission and reservoir hosts of Chagas Disease. In Trypanosomiasis and Leishmaniasis with Special Reference to Chagas Disease, CIBA Foundation Symposium 20, Elsevier Excerpta Medica North Holland, Amsterdam, 1974, 51.

2. Zeledon, R., et al. Biology and ethnology of _Triatoma dimidiate_ (Latreille, 1811). III. Habitat and blood sources. J Exp Entomol 10; 363, 1973.

3. Gomez-Nunez, J.C. Resting places, dispersal, and survival of CO-60-tagged adult Rhodnius prolixus. J Med Entomol 6; 83, 1969.

4. Immunology of Chagas Disease. Bull WHO 50; 459, 1974.

5. Wood, S.F. and Wood, F.D. Observations on vectors of Chagas Disease in the United States. III. New Mexico. Am J Trop Med Hyg 10; 155, 1961.

6. Burkholder, J.E., et al. _Trypanosoma cruzi_ (Chagas) (Protozoa: Kinetoplastida) in invertebrate, reservoir and human hosts of the lower Rio Grande valley of Texas. J Parasitol 66; 305, 1980.

7. Woody, N.C. and Woody, H.B. American trypanosomiasis (Chagas disease); first indigenous case in the United States. JAMA 159; 676, 1955.

8. Ochs, D.E., et al. Postmortem diagnosis of autochthonous acute chagasic myocarditis by polymerase chain reaction amplification of a species-specific DNA sequence of _Trypanosoma cruzi_. Am J Trop Med Hyg 54; 526, 1996.

9. Herwaldt, B.L., et al. Use of polymerase chain reaction to diagnose the fifth reported US case of autochthonous transmission of _Trypanosoma cruzi_, in Tennessee, 1998. J Infect Dis 181; 395, 2000.

10. Schiffler, R.J., et al. Indigenous Chagas disease (American trypanosomiasis) in California. JAMA 251; 2983, 1984.

11. Walton, B.C., et al. The isolation and identification of _Trypanosoma cruzi_ from raccoons in Maryland. Am J Trop Med Hyg 7; 603, 1958.

